[{"location":"reference/#Reference","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.DiagHamInterface","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.DiagHamInterface","text":"Interface to the DiagHam library.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.execute_diagham_script-Tuple{AbstractString}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.execute_diagham_script","text":"execute_diagham_script(execute; kwargs...)\n\nRun a DiagHam executable. Kwargs are converted to CLI flags (_ → -). Single-char keys use -k, multi-char use --key. Boolean true adds flag, false omits.\n\nThe kwargs of Cmd() are supported.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.fix_fileending-Tuple{AbstractString, AbstractString}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.fix_fileending","text":"fix_fileending(filename, ending)\n\nReturn filename ensuring it ends with ending.\n\nIf ending does not start with a dot, a dot is prepended. If ending is empty, the original filename is returned. The function is safe to call with full paths; it only checks the final characters of filename.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.format_with_precision-Tuple{T} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.format_with_precision","text":"format_with_precision(x; atol=eps(float(T)), mode=:auto, maxdigits=20)\n\nFormat number x as a string with absolute precision atol. Mode :auto uses %f for [1e-3, 1e6), else %e. Use :f or :e to force format.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.get_diagham_path-Tuple{}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.get_diagham_path","text":"get_diagham_path()\n\nGet the current path to the DiagHam build directory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.install_diagham-Tuple{}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.install_diagham","text":"install_diagham(; source_dir, build_dir=nothing, run_dir=nothing, configure_options=[\"--enable-fqhe\",\"--enable-fti\",\"--with-blas-libs=-lopenblas\",\"--with-lapack-libs=\",\"--enable-lapack\"])\n\nCheckout and build DiagHam from source. Returns the path to the build directory.\n\nParameters are keyword-only and intended to be easily overridden from tests or user code.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.read_matrix_from_txt-Tuple{String}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.read_matrix_from_txt","text":"read_matrix_from_txt(filename; sparsity=0.1)\n\nRead Hamiltonian from DiagHam-format text file. Auto-detects real/complex. Returns dense matrix if non-zero fraction > sparsity, else sparse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.set_diagham_path-Tuple{Any}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.set_diagham_path","text":"set_diagham_path(path)\n\nSet the path to the DiagHam build directory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.write_matrix_elements-Tuple{Any, Any, Any, String}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.write_matrix_elements","text":"write_matrix_elements(label, indices, coeffs, file_name; dropband=false, full_single_particle=false)\n\nWrite matrix elements to DiagHam-format file with header and data rows. dropband=true removes band index for single-band data. full_single_particle=true keeps both band indices for one-body terms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt-Tuple{SparseArrays.SparseMatrixCSC, String}","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt","text":"Optimized write_to_txt for SparseMatrixCSC. Converts to CSR internally.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractMatrix{T}, String}} where T<:Number","page":"Reference","title":"DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt","text":"write_to_txt(Ham, filename; atol)\n\nWrite Hamiltonian matrix to DiagHam-format text file (sparse coordinate format, 0-based indexing). Elements with abs(val) ≤ atol are omitted. Existing files are backed up.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"index/#Index","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#DiagHamInterface.jl","page":"Home","title":"DiagHamInterface.jl","text":"DiagHamInterface.jl is a Julia package that provides an interface to DiagHam, a suite of exact diagonalization programs for quantum many-body systems.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"Home","title":"Installation","text":"The package is not yet registered in the Julia general registry. It can be installed trough the package manager with the following command:\n\npkg> add git@github.com:ManyBodyLab/DiagHamInterface.jl.git","category":"section"},{"location":"#Code-Samples","page":"Home","title":"Code Samples","text":"julia> using DiagHamInterface\njulia> open(\"pseudopotentials.dat\", \"w\") do io\n           write(io, \"Pseudopotentials = 0.0 1.0 \\n\")\n       end\njulia> execute_diagham_script(\n           \"FQHE/src/Programs/FQHEOnTorus/FQHETorusFermionsTwoBodyGeneric\";\n           p = 3,        # Number of particles\n           l = 9,        # Number of flux quanta (N_phi = p * q = 3 * 3 = 9 for 1/3 filling)\n           interaction_file = \"pseudopotentials.dat\",\n           interaction_name = \"V1\",\n       )\njulia> A = rand(ComplexF64,100, 100); Ham = A' * A; # Create a random positive definite Hamiltonian\njulia> write_to_txt(A, \"hamiltonian.txt\") # Write Hamiltonian to text file\njulia> execute_diagham_script(\n           \"src/Programs/GenericHamiltonianDiagonalization\";\n           c = true,\n           data_columns = 2,\n           use_lapack = true,\n           hamiltonian = \"hamiltonian.txt\",\n           o = \"spectrum.txt\",\n           all_eigenstates = true,\n           eigenstate_file = \"eigenstates.txt\",\n       )","category":"section"},{"location":"#License","page":"Home","title":"License","text":"DiagHamInterface.jl is licensed under the APL2 License. By using or interacting with this software in any way, you agree to the license of this software.\n\n\n\nThis page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"section"}]
